Ms Fraker said the violation was calculated from the minute she walked through the sliding doors.

'When I was getting out of the car, he was leaving the store,' she said. 'As soon as he saw me walk into the store, he turned around and went back inside.'

Despite his strange behaviour, she said she shrugged it off and kept on shopping.

'He got in line behind me,' Ms Fraker 
said. 'I gave him the opportunity to go in front of me because I wasn't 
ready to check out and he said "oh, no, you go ahead."'

